<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n44153g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n44" href="#n44153g">N44 (VI.B.34)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n44all.htm#n44153g"> 153(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> The Cairn of The / Cul Turned to I&mdash;</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">In point of fact, <font color="green">[Columcille]</font> revisited Ireland more than once &hellip; still, for thirty-four years the Islet of Iona was his permanent abode. There is a legend that he navigated from one island to another until he finally ran his curragh into the little bay known as Port-na-Curraich. From the hill above&mdash;Carn-cul-ri-Erin, the Cairn of the Backside turned to Ireland&mdash;he was satisfied he could no longer descry his native shores, and there amid the silence of the seas he built his monastery. <small> F.J. Sheed, ed. <a name="FJSI" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#FJSI"><cite title="source">The Irish Way</cite></a> (May 1932) [<font size="-1">ST. COLUMCILLE</font> (521-597)] 52</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
